<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Center Director Welcomes Russian-U.S. Exercises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Center Director Welcomes Russian-U.S. Exercises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105080494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0653 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 11 TASS -- Director of the Russian 
Military and Analytical Centre, Aleksandr Konovalov, believes 
that joint Russo-U.S. exercises on the Totsk test-site near the 
city of Orenburg will help bring the people of the two countries 
closer together. In an interview with ITAR-TASS Konovalov said 
that any "statements against conducting the maneuvers are 
prompted, primarily, by situational and political considerations 
and do not meet Russia's national interests." 
  According to the military analyst, statements alleging that 
the U.S. intends to "find out" Russia's secrets during the 
exercises are groundless as well. He rejected speculations 
alleging that Americans are interested in obtaining documents 
about an air nuclear explosion above the test-site made by the 
former Soviet Union in the 1950s. According to Konovalov, the 
results of an investigation into after-effects of the explosion 
were made public and are no longer secret. Besides, a group of 
scientists had recently worked on the test-site and the results 
of their work were published and contain no secrets for the 
world public. 
  Konovolov believes that the exercises of peace-keeping 
forces 
are of principal importance since Russian troops will inevitably 
have to carry out joint peace-keeping operations, while until 
now Russian soldiers and officers had not received sufficient 
experience. There is nothing wrong if a battalion, a regiment 
or a division take a training course using methods worked out by 
the best experts and experienced officers from Russia and the 
United States, Konovalov said. 
  Such training exercises will help many Russian servicemen 
from a peace-keeping contingent to survive, he said. "The 
military will be offered a wonderful chance to communicate, to 
know each other better and it will be the best way of bringing 
the people of the two countries closer together, making war go 
back into the past," Konovalov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

