<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Official on Ukraine, Crimea Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Official on Ukraine, Crimea Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005185194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1746 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The chairman of the State Duma committee for CIS 
matters, Konstantin Zatulin, has warned against rushing 
presidential elections in Ukraine which would endanger calm and 
stability in the republic. In an interview with 
INTERFAX-Ukraine Tuesday, he pointed out he was referring to 
Russia's experience of aggravated relations between different 
branches of state power which should be taken into account in 
Ukraine. 
  "With great difficulty, we have surmounted the worst. 
Actually, the first stage of civil war in Russia has taken 
place," Zatulin was quoted as saying. 
  The interviewee said Russia would conclude "the most 
extensive agreements, the most extensive trade and economic 
ties" with Crimea. 
  A number of unsolved issues remain, the main one being the 
future of the Black Sea Fleet and Sevastopol, he said. "Without 
support from both Russia and Ukraine, Sevastopol will find 
itself in the most difficult situation," he said. 
  Zatulin did not preclude "Russia proposing to Crimea 
participation in a package of programs, in the first place 
economic ones." The Russian deputy has been participating in the 
Crimean parliament's session since its opening. 

</TEXT>

