<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Envoy Blames Estonia for Talks Impasse </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Envoy Blames Estonia for Talks Impasse </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105103094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0921 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 11 TASS -- The Russian-Estonian 
negotiations on the withdrawal of troops are now in a blind 
alley as concerns both military and humanitarian issues 
involved, head of the Russian delegation, Ambassador Vasiliy 
Svirin said in an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS today. No 
headway was made in last week's round of talks because of the 
"non-constructive approach of the Estonian side," the ambassador 
said. 
  "The Estonian side has gone back on its earlier statements 
which Russia regarded as a basis for the withdrawal of the 
troops before August 31," the ambassador said, referring to the 
statement made by the Estonian delegation head during the 14th 
round of talks, who went on record as saying that the agreed 
provisions concerning military pensioners remained in force 
despite the fact that they were at variance with some clauses of 
the law on citizenship of Estonia". 
  In the present situation there is no need to mislead the 
public opinion and continue "negotiations for the sake of 
negotiations". For this reason the Russian delegation has come 
up with a new proposal. Each of the for main working groups -- 
on humanitarian and legal, military, economic, and border issues 
-- must prepare new versions and formulas in May to pull the 
negotiations out of the impasse. Only when it becomes clear 
that serious shifts are in the offing, the date can be set for 
the next round of talks, the ambassador said. 
  Russia has no "excessive claims" concerning social insurance 
for military pensioners and their families residing in Estonia. 
Moscow's position on this is analogous to that it upheld in 
negotiations with Latvia. A mutually acceptable solution was 
found in those talks and Russia and Latvia signed a package of 
agreements, the ambassador recalled. The successful outcome was 
made possible thanks to the political will of the two countries 
and their readiness for sensible compromise solutions, he said. 

</TEXT>

