<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian-Estonian Fishing Agreements Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian-Estonian Fishing Agreements Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1105093594 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 11 May 94 p 
4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1105093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Igor Petrov: "Fishing Quota Will Be Established </F>
in Baltic"] 
  [Text] After two years of painstaking preparatory work a 
package of agreements relating to cooperation in the fishing 
sphere has been signed between the Russian and Estonian 
governments. 
  One of these agreements is designed to promote the 
normalization of fishing in the Baltic while another concerns 
the reciprocal use and safeguarding of fish stocks in inland 
border lakes. 
  The agreement, signed for a period of five years with an 
automatic extension, in contrast to many similar documents also 
contains a mechanism for monitoring the documents' punctilious 
fulfillment. In the opinion of Vladimir Korelskiy, chairman of 
the committee for fishing, the next step will be to establish 
scientifically substantiated fishing quotas in the Baltic and to 
elaborate measures to safeguard a fish rated as a delicacy -- 
the smelt -- in the Chudskoye, Teploye, and Pskovskoye Lakes. 
  What draws the attention is the fact that the agreements on 
the solution of practical isues affecting the two countries' 
interests were signed before Russia and Estonia had unanimously 
decided to establish offifcial borders between the states. 
  Obviously fishermen understand better than politicians that 
while the case drags one the fish, which recognize no state 
borders, could be swimming off other shores. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

