<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Visit South Kurils Without Visas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japanese Visit South Kurils Without Visas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105085194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0812 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo May 11 TASS -- This year's first group of 
Japanese has left for the South Kurils in accordance with the 
programme of the visa-free exchanges between these Russian 
islands and Japan, which began two years ago. 
  The ship, which sailed today from the port of Nemuro, north 
Hokkaido, to the Kunashir island, is bringing in 48 people, 
including 24 former Japanese inhabitants of the Kuril Islands, 
nine representatives of the national movement for the return of 
the "northern territories", and 15 journalists. 
  During their stay on the Kunashir island, the Japanese 
guests 
will meet local inhabitants, will visit a secondary school and 
several enterprises. Like the previous groups of Japanese 
guests, they will live in the homes of local citizens. The 
delegation will return home on May 13. This year's second group 
of Japanese visitors will come to the Kunashir island on the 
next day after its arrival in Japan. 
  The third season of visa-free exchanges began for the 
citizens of the Kuril Islands this April, when Hokkaido was 
visited by this year's first group of Russians. The same number 
of people is expected to take part in visa-free exchanges 
between the two countries this year as in 1993, that is 400 
people from each side. A distinctive feature of the 1994 season 
is that this year's delegations will include more specialists, 
able to use their trips to the neighbouring country to exchange 
professional experience. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

