<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Presidential Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Presidential Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005185694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1746 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A group of members of Ukraine's newly-elected 
parliament are going to propose an amendment to the Constitution 
to strip the president of much of his authority, according to 
Rukh party leader Vyacheslav Chernovil. 
  In that case the president would only be the head of state 
and not the head of state and government as today, Chernovil 
told a news conference in Kiev on Tuesday. 
  He said it would hardly be possible to postpone the 
presidential election, something proposed by President Leonid 
Kravchuk, because a motion to that effect would need the support 
of at least 170 legislators and because the preparations for the 
26 June election "have already gone too far." Nevertheless 
Chernovil expects the matter to be brought up at one of initial 
parliament sessions. 
  At the same time, he said he considered it "immoral" to hold 
a presidential election before the legislature delineated the 
future president's powers. 
  Chernovil said his party would not propose its own candidate 
to the post of parliamentary speaker "unless the Communists 
nominate their own candidate." 
  According to the Central Electoral Commission, Rukh has won 
20 seats in the new parliament, or 5.9 percent of the total 
number. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

