<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on New Crimean Parliament Speaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on New Crimean Parliament Speaker </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005191694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1627 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As a longer range priority, Crimea must be an 
independent legal entity and form a closer union with Russia, 
leader of the local Republican Party Sergey [Serhiy] Tsekov told 
parliament on Tuesday. He believes the idea of such a union 
must be legislated upon. 
  On Tuesday, the parliament's largest Russia faction holding 
55 out of the 98 seats overwhelmingly approved Tsekov's 
candidacy for the speaker's post. 
  Tsekov himself prefers a safer option providing for 
appropriate agreements to be signed with Ukraine and Russia and 
whatever laws needed to be adopted. 
  His rival Vladimir Klychnikov has called for a balance of 
forces in parliament and the society. 
  On the diplomatic front, priority must be given to Russia 
given that the emerging situation is good for Crimea's movement 
towards Moscow, he said. Klychnikov thinks Crimea must take 
advantage of the current situation when unification trends 
pervail both in the Russian and Ukrainian parliaments. 
  The deputies are expected to elect a new speaker later 
today. 

</TEXT>

