<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Acting Prime Minister Denies Economic Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Acting Prime Minister Denies Economic Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1105113594 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 7 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1105113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Yu. Zvyahilskyy: `It Is By Force of </F>
Habit That We Speak About the Crisis'"] 
  [Text] Whereas inflation reached 91 percent in December 
1993, it was 19.2 percent in January 1994; 12.6 percent in 
February; and 5.7 percent in March. This enabled us to adopt a 
decision on reducing the annual rate of the National Bank to 210 
percent. At the same time, it is possible to regard the 
catastrophic decline in the volume of production from a 
different point of view: The decrease in the production of 
electric energy, for example, amounts to just 18 percent, while 
the production of some foodstuffs and the output of individual 
branches of the national economy, including metallurgy, is even 
increasing. These and other facts were quoted to correspondents 
by acting Prime Minister Yu. Zvyahilskyy during a meeting in the 
UNIAN office. 
  According to Zvyahilskyy, the government currently controls 
the situation on the currency and credits and finance markets 
and has come out decisively against the resumption of auctions 
at the Interbank Currency Exchange, which would ensure a free 
exchange rate of the Ukrainian karbovanets relative to the U.S. 
dollar. In his opinion, this is risky as long as the energy 
sources account for 68.9 percent in the country's import and 
there exists a real threat that the prices on the consumer 
market may get out of control. For the same reason, "it is 
necessary to be more cautious in accepting recommendations and 
demands of international financial organizations." 
  Asked by a correspondent "if everything is so good, then why 
are we talking about a crisis?" Yu. Zvyahilskyy shrugged his 
shoulders: "Force of habit." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61943 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov091_f_94012" </HT>


