<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Appeals to Deputies for Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Appeals to Deputies for Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005130394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1058 
GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1005130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 10 May (ITAR-TASS) -- President Boris 
Yeltsin of Russia signed a federal law 8 May "On the status of a 
deputy of the Federation Council and the status of a deputy of 
the State Duma of the Russian Federation Federal Assembly." In 
this connection the president of Russia also sent a letter to 
deputies of the Federation Council and the State Duma. The text 
of this document, which was released by the presidential press 
service today, follows: 
  "Esteemed deputies! 
  "Today I signed the federal law `On the status of a deputy 
of 
the Federation Council and the status of a deputy of the State 
Duma of the Russian Federation Federal Assembly'. 
  "This was a difficult decision, in as far as some juridical 
aspects evidently require further revision and some are not in 
line with the Constitution; and there are prerequisites which 
the electorate could justifiably condemn. 
  "But there is something else I understand, too: you and your 
aides need of the law as a whole, it is necessary for effective 
legislative work. 
  "At the same time I understand that we need to live not only 
in accord with one another, but also in accord with the 
Constitution and the law. I am therefore following up this 
letter with a list of amendments which would have been submitted 
to you had I rejected the law. As guarantor of the 
Constitution, I propose you should suspend the validity of those 
normative acts which contravene the Constitution. Following 
this, I believe it to be necessary to examine the proposals 
submitted, including those which fall within the context of 
conciliation procedures, and to adopt these as amendments to the 
law currently in effect without waiting for decisions of the 
Constitutional Court. 
  "I regard this decision as one of the steps toward 
implementing the Treaty on Public Accord. I therefore believe 
it is necessary to make this letter public. 
  "Esteemed deputies! I am counting on your wisdom and 
understanding, and I hope for further fruitful cooperation." 
  [Signed] B. Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

