<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `War of Monsters' Between Security Ministries Denied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `War of Monsters' Between Security Ministries Denied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105091194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0857 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105091194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Larisa Kislinskaya] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 11 TASS -- Rumours about "a war of 
monsters" are over-exaggerated, spokesmen for the Russian 
Interior Ministry and the Federal Counterintelligence Service, 
Vladimir Vorozhtsov and Aleksandr Mikhaylov, told a briefing in 
Moscow today. 
  They were referring to press reports about criminal 
proceedings initiated by the Federal Counterintelligence Service 
against some high-ranking officials of the Ministry of Internal 
Affairs. 
  The spokesmen said the federal service had indeed detained 
some officials, including the former official of the Directorate 
for Punitive Action of the Moscow region administration, a 
senior investigator and a lawyer. They were caught in the 
action while handing over a major sum of money in hard currency 
and later charged with an array of crimes. But this does not 
amount to a war between the ministry and the federal service, 
the spokesman said. 
  Last year 359 criminal proceedings were initiated against 
security officials, mostly by the Interior Ministry. Twenty-two 
legal actions were brought jointly with the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service. This year 142 crimes were 
registered by the Interior Ministry. In eight cases, action was 
taken jointly with federal service agents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

