<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll on Support for Presidential Candidates Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll on Support for Presidential Candidates Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1105104194 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1715 
GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1105104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Even on days off the upcoming elections of the first 
Belarusian president remain a popular topic among Vitebsk 
residents. The Vitebsk independent sociological agency Istina 
decided to make some preliminary conclusions regarding the 
results of its nonofficial poll. It conducted a selective phone 
poll of 364 Vitebsk residents. Already at the start the 
sociologists discovered an interesting detail: In Vitebsk 
primarily women hold control over home phones. Therefore, the 
prevailing majority of respondents is represented by the best 
half of mankind of various age and professions. They gave their 
sympathies to three leading politicians: Alyaksandr Lukashenka, 
Vyachaslaw Kebich, and Stanislaw Shushkevich. The remaining 
candidates for this prestigious post were much behind the 
leaders. Almost half of the respondents link their hopes for 
improving the situation in society and the economy with the 
president. However, one fourth of the respondents did not 
express any positive emotions regarding this issue. 

</TEXT>

