<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Imported Energy Debts Top $117 Million </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Imported Energy Debts Top $117 Million </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1205083094 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 12 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK1205083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "In Brief" rubric: "Energy </F>
Debt Mounting"] 
  [Text] A situation close to disastrous has taken shape in 
Kazakhstan's fuel and energy complex. Its imported fuel debts 
have topped $117 million. Reporting this, the Republic's 
business newspaper PANORAMA gives the list of Kazakhstan's 
energy creditors, which are Kirgizia [Kyrgyzstan], Turkmenistan, 
Uzbekistan, and Russia. The lion's share of the debts falls on 
the Uzbek side: Kazakhstan owes it more than $100 million for 
the use of natural gas and electricity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

