Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Cease-fire Agreed for Nagorno-Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Cease-fire Agreed for Nagorno-Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205101194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0943 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205101194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 12 May TASS -- A new cease-fire agreement 
beginning on midnight from 11 to 12 May has been mediated among 
the warring sides by Russia and the CSCE at talks in Moscow. 
  Russian envoy on Karabakh settlement Vladimir Kazimirov told 
TASS on Thursday that in contrast to the last cease-fire, which 
was unilaterally declared by Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan, 
the latest one is a commitment of three parties, a compromise 
brokered by mediators among Azerbaijan, Armenia and 
Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  "Multiple violations of previous agreements put the trust to 
political will of the leaders of the sides under a serious 
test," Kazimirov admitted. 
  He said that the agreement was signed by defence ministers 
of 
Azerbaijan, Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh. The Russian Foreign 
Ministry welcomes the cease-fire and insists on its 
unconditional fulfilment by all parties, he added. 
  "It is necessary to ensure a radical breakthrough in the 
situation, a firm turn towards peace, to consolidate armistice 
by reliable and legally-binding agreements on the final end of 
the armed conflict," the envoy stressed. 
  So far there have been no reports about violations of the 
cease-fire. 
  Later in the day Kazimirov, Chairman of the CSCE Minsk Group 
for Karabakh Jan Elison and his deputy Mathias Mosberg are 
leaving for the conflict area to meet leaders of Azerbaijan, 
Armenia, and Nagorno-Karabakh. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-61984 </DOCNO>
