<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Says Legislation Out of Date </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Says Legislation Out of Date </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105171094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1438 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy, edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze has said that 
the republic's legislation is outdated. In a message to 
parliament, the Georgian leader asked deputies to take urgent 
measures to form new economic relations. This is an obligatory 
condition for the formation and development of the Georgian 
statehood, he believes. 
  Shevardnadze says in his message that the government is to 
submit shortly to parliament three different types of bills 
which should be given particular attention. 
  The first package refers to economic relations, the second 
one to the bills on legal guarantees for the protection of the 
rights of the economic subjects which take part in material 
relations. The third package has laws which, in line with the 
democratic course chosen by Georgia, should regulate 
relationships among branches of power. 
  The message says that parliament should adopt also codes of 
civil laws, criminal and labor laws as well as laws on 
administrative violations of laws. 
  As the speaker of parliament I am prepared, to speed up the 
process of law-making, to cooperate with all commissions, 
factions and individual deputies, says the message. 

</TEXT>

