<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Urges Maintaining Stability </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105142294 Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network in Lithuanian 
1300 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius Network </F>
<F P=105>  Lithuanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] A statement by Adolfas Slezevicius, prime 
minister and chairman of the ruling Democratic Labour Party, was 
made public today. 
  The statement says that in the current situation of fragile 
stability in the state of Lithuania, the idea of early Seimas 
elections proposed by the Tautininkai Union and the Democratic 
Party has in essence been dictated by petty party interests and 
not by the interests of the state and the nation. 
  The most important thing now is stability in the state, the 
prime minister maintains. According to him, signs of economic 
and political stability can now be clearly seen in Lithuania, 
and this is testified by the significantly reduced inflation, 
stable national currency, and the formation of governmental 
structures. 
  Adolfas Slezevicius says that western confidence in 
Lithuania 
is growing and that investments are growing, too. This is the 
prospect for improving the currently hard life, the leader of 
the ruling party said. 
  According to the statement, early Seimas elections would be 
bring about yet more political and spiritual confusion, 
unnecessary budget expenditure, and would waste people's 
efforts. [passage omitted] 

