<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Urges German Help With Financial Integration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Urges German Help With Financial Integration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205123294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1115 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Bonn May 12 TASS -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
wants Germany which is to chair the European Union from July to 
promote its integration into international financial 
institutions. 
  "Russia should be pulled closer in Naples", Yeltsin told 
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel at the end of their Thursday 
meeting referring to the G-7 summit scheduled for July. 
  "We shall try as much as it is possible", Waigel promised in 
return. 
  According to Russian Economics Minister Aleksandr Shokhin, 
Yeltsin wants the G-7 to analyse the forms of insuring 
investments in Russia from noncommercial risks. He told TASS 
that the Russian leader had raised the issue at the G-7 summit 
in Tokyo, but "unfortunately the European Union is only now 
getting down to the work". 
  Shokhin added that the problems of Russian foreign debt in 
the framework of the London and Paris Clubs of creditors were 
discussed during Yeltsin's meeting with Waigel. 
  Waigel, in his turn, told TASS that the debt problem will be 
discussed in detail at his talks with Shokhin. According to 
him, Yeltsin expressed his gratitude for efficient work in 
attracting international financial institutions to reforming 
Russian economy. 
  He also said that the Russian pullout from Germany will not 
"alienate the peoples" of the two countries. "On the contrary, 
this step already now causes sympathy to Russia among citizens 
and political parties of our country", the finance minister 
stressed. 
  After the meeting with Waigel Yeltsin left for Helmut Kohl's 
home region of Rhineland-Palatinate where he is to hold several 
private meetings with the chancellor. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

