<H3> <TI>   Grachev on Need To Hold Joint U.S.-Russian Exercises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev on Need To Hold Joint U.S.-Russian Exercises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105200194 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1830 GMT 
11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Slavyanka" program of the Russian Defense </F>
Ministry] 
  [Text] The fate of the Russian-U.S. joint command and staff 
exercises on the Totskoye test range near Orenburg remains 
unclear. There is a fairly broad range of opinions being voiced 
on this issue. At times it is even acquiring a fashionable 
political nuance. Here, however, is the opinion of Army General 
Pavel Grachev, the Russian defense minister: 
  [Begin Grachev recording] What a rumpus has now been raised 
about these exercises! We signed the agreement a year ago, and 
everyone remained silent. Now certain people have suddenly 
remembered them and there has been a hullabaloo in the State 
Duma, and there has been a stir at government level, and even in 
the [Russian Federation] Security Council. Advice is being 
extended to the president. Boris Nikolayevich and I have also 
discussed this issue and what approach to take to it. 
  If we really want mutually to get the enemy image out of our 
heads and really move step-by-step toward partnership, the 
exercises are, of course, necessary. Let the young American set 
his eyes on the young Russian. Let them have contact with one 
another. Let them tell each other about their lives. What, in 
the final analysis, is wrong in that? Moreover, they are not 
war exercises in the pure sense, but peacekeeping command and 
staff exercises, peacekeeping exercises, and, if we really 
respect one another and respect those people for whose sake we 
are engaging in peacekeeping activities, then even at the moral 
level these exercises should be held. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

