<H3> <TI>   General on Black Sea Fleet, Joint U.S. Exercises </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    General on Black Sea Fleet, Joint U.S. Exercises </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105211894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1247 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 11 May -- The Black Sea Fleet problem has 
moved beyond the departmental framework and assumed state 
importance. A system of radical proposals on the future of the 
fleet is now being prepared by the Ministries of Foreign 
Affairs, Defense, Economy, and others. The proposals will be 
examined at the highest level, Lieutenant General Valeriy 
Manilov, deputy secretary of the Russian Federation Security 
Council, said in an interview with an ITAR-TASS correspondent. 
  According to him, it is also impossible to resolve the 
question of conducting the joint Russian-U.S. command and staff 
exercises on a departmental level. We need to analyze the 
political, economic, military-technical, and financial aspects 
of the exercises, the general said. 
  Conclusions and suggestions that should also give 
consideration to the general public opinion should form the 
basis of decisions on the future of the Black Sea Fleet and on 
holding the Russian-U.S. military exercises, Manilov stressed. 
He said that the Security Council has already made its position 
clear to the Russian president, but at the same time, did not 
reveal the essence of this position. 

</TEXT>

