<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greenpeace Ship Causes `Scandal' at Vladivostok </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greenpeace Ship Causes `Scandal' at Vladivostok </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205082394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0626 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205082394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Eduard Popov] </F>
  [Text] Vladivostok May 12 TASS -- Confrontation between the 
Vladivostok border guard service and representatives from the 
international Greenpeace organisation, who arrived in the 
maritime territory to drum up support for the protection of the 
Ussuri taiga from massive log felling and industrial pollution, 
is turning into a scandal. 
  A Greenpeace ship cannot leave the Vladivostok port for the 
Svetlaya Bay for the fourth day to inspect activities of the 
Russian-South Korean log felling enterprise. 
  Operating in compliance with Russian legislation, border 
guards approved the call only for the ship's crew members. 
  However, the bulk of the delegation consists of ecologists, 
researchers and journalists who are, in actual fact, passengers 
and, according to Russian laws, have no right to cross Russian 
territorial waters. 
  Commenting on the situation, head of the Vladivostok port 
check point Oleg Sukhanov claimed that the Greenpeace 
deliberately earns scandalous popularity on the conflict with 
authorities. 
  The ship with crew members may go to the bay without any 
problems. The rest of the delegation may go to the bay (some 
500 kilometers from Vladivostok) by other types of 
transportation, for instance, by air. 
  "Despite my great respect for the international `Greens' 
movement, we cannot permit a violation of Russian legislation on 
the protection of the state border," the border guard stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

