<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Views MiG Sale to Malaysia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Official Views MiG Sale to Malaysia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105162794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1511 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Bychkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 11 TASS--"The Russian side is satisfied 
with practically everything in the deal to sell Malaysia 18 
MiG-29 fighters and Moscow considers it beneficial," a Russian 
Foreign Ministry top official said. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Wednesday, Anatoliy 
Khmelnitskiy, head of the second Asia department of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, said that "presently, the Russian-Malaysian 
deal estimated at about 600 million U.S. dollars is at the final 
stage of consideration. There are no serious obstacles for its 
signing." 
  A Russian delegation led by Deputy Foreign Minister 
Aleksandr 
Panov has just returned from Malaysia where it held a series of 
fruitful meetings and talks. They aimed at specifying the 
details of a large package of agreements now in the works, 
Khmelnitskiy said. 
  Apart from selling MiG fighters to Malaysia, the sides also 
discussed the possibility of launching the production of spare 
parts for them in Malaysia. Bilateral agreements between the 
two countries have committed them to establish a sound 
maintenance base and teach Malaysian pilots to fly Russian MiG 
fighters. 
  Malaysia will pay part of the deal with palm oil. "This fact 
must not worry Russian people. Malaysian palm oil is not only a 
highly nutritious product, but is also indispensable in various 
industries, including aerospace industry," Khmelnitskiy said. 
  If the deal goes through, Malaysia will be the first 
Southeast Asian country to be granted access to Russian weapons 
and military technologies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

