<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on State Duma Budget Bill Debate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on State Duma Budget Bill Debate </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Defense Budget Undecided </H4>

<F P=102> LD1105144494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1407 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 11 May -- Today's State Duma debate on the 
defense budget has been marked by sharp exchanges, and the final 
figure for Russia's military expenditure has not yet been 
defined, ITAR-TASS was told by Colonel General Vasiliy Vorobev, 
head of the Defense Ministry's Military Budget and Finance Main 
Directorate. He said the difference between the sum being 
requested and the sum on offer is so great that the armed 
forces' continued existence is at stake. For example, the 
Russian Defense Ministry is asking for 87 trillion rubles, while 
the Ministry of Finance is insisting on allocating just 37 
trillion rubles. 
  According to the Defense Ministry, the Finance Ministry has 
pared spending on the military to the bone. Arrears have been 
run up on all major expenditure items. The military is now in 
the position of having insufficient funds, not only to pay 
salaries, but also to buy food and equipment and to pay its 
bills. Lengthy delays in issuing servicemen's pay packets are 
now routine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

