<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-092 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Passes Law on Foreign Debt, Credits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Duma Passes Law on Foreign Debt, Credits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105193994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1618 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma passed a federal law on state foreign 
debts and Russia's credits granted to foreign states in the 
first hearing Wednesday. 
  The draft law provides for an annual setting by a federal 
law 
of the maximum volume of credits used within a fiscal year and 
representing part of Russia's foreign debt. The maximum volume 
of foreign loans taken by the state shall not exceed the annual 
volume of payments in service and repayment of Russia's foreign 
debt. 
  The draft law envisions that Russia's international treaties 
on state loans and Russia's state credits to foreign states are 
subject to ratification whenever they exceed 100 million dollars. 
  The State Duma also passed a federal law on the maximum 
volume of state loans and Russia's state credits to foreign 
states in 1994 Wednesday. 
  According to the law, the maximum volume of Russia's loans 
in 
1994 is set at 4.7 billion dollars, while Russia's credits to 
foreign states in 1994 at 400 million dollars. 
  The two federal laws were sent for consideration by the 
Federation Council, the upper house of the Russian parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

