<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Examines Yeltsin Remarks on Deputy Status Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Examines Yeltsin Remarks on Deputy Status Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205100594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0854 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 12 TASS -- The Russian State Duma began 
examining President Yeltsin's remarks on the Duma deputy status 
law. The Duma part of the Russian parliament's Conciliation 
Commission was formed today. It is headed by vice-Speaker of 
the State Duma Valentin Kovalev. The commission also include 
the authors of the law -- Chairman of the Duma Organisational 
Committee Vladimir Bauer, his deputy Igor Shichanin, and also 
members of the Duma Committee for Legisaltion professors of law 
Viktor Vishnyakov and Oleg Mironov. 
  "The commission has already begun its work," Valentin 
Kovalev 
told ITAR-TASS. Asked when it will be completed, he replied 
that "quite a few subtle constitutional and legislative problems 
have cropped up". Kovalev noted that "all this process is most 
extraordinary, because the president recommends the State Duma 
to suspend the action of several norms". He recalled that "the 
procedure for such a suspension was not envisaged by the 
constitutional legislation. This is why the Duma is confronted 
with several extremely difficult problems affecting its reaction 
to the letter even though it is most favourably disposed towards 
it". 
  Kovalev said that "it was first of all necessary to solve 
several procedural matters, in other words to establish our 
competence to suspend these norms and then to get down to the 
crux of the matter". He stressed that a solution would be found 
within the frameworks of the Conciliation Commission, which will 
"satisfy the Council of the Federation, the State Duma, and the 
president". 
  Kovalev said that the president's remarks were "quite 
extensive" and included almost six typewritten pages. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

