<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Khasbulatov Favors Stabilizing Russian-Chechen Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Khasbulatov Favors Stabilizing Russian-Chechen Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105123394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1109 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On May 9 (Victory Day) former Russian Supreme Soviet 
speaker Ruslan Khasbulatov met Chechen citizens in the mountain 
village of Benoy (southeastern Chechnya, 100 kilometers away 
from Groznyy - IF). Interfax learned that more than 20,000 
people, including inhabitants of neighboring Dagestan showed up 
at the rally. 
  Khasbulatov emphasized the necessity for normalization of 
relations with Russia. He suggested that this would contribute 
to stabilization of the situation in Chechnya and would bring 
positive changes in the lives of the Chechen poor. He stressed 
that the peoples must not suffer from the ambitions of certain 
politicians. 
  A deputy Chechen interior minister who was present at the 
rally called this an appeal to be within the composition of 
Russia and urged that there be no speculation on this sensitive 
issue. Khasbulatov replied that he had just expressed his 
opinion. "Issues on state relations are not solved during 
rallies," he remarked. 
  The Chechen presidential structures told Interfax that the 
appeal by Khasbulatov had received practically no support. 

</TEXT>

