<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk: Parliament Should Decide on Election Date </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk: Parliament Should Decide on Election Date </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105122694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1109 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk believes that 
the priority task of the first session of the new Supreme Soviet 
is to determine the issue on the June presidential elections, 
namely whether to hold them on June 26, as the previous 
parliament decided, or after the adoption of the necessary 
legislative basis. 
  During his meeting with the deputies of the new parliament 
on 
Tuesday in Kiev Kravchuk expressed the opinion that "from the 
very beginning the Supreme Soviet should pay attention to the 
conclusion of the work over Ukraine's new Constitution." 
  "The absence of a new Constitution makes the state's 
building 
and the work on choosing authorities for the various branches of 
power difficult," noted Kravchuk. 
  In his words, under the current situation the people will 
come to the elections having no notion "what the results will 
be." 
  At the same time Kravchuk pointed out that "it will be 
difficult to adopt the Constitution as a whole because "it is 
necessary to at least adopt serious well-balanced decrees on 
separate institutions of power to give reliable legal support to 
the election campaign." 

</TEXT>

