<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Travkin Explains Appointment as Government Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Travkin Explains Appointment as Government Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105151594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1347 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nikolay Travkin, leader of the Democratic Party 
parliamentary group, told Interfax that he had been appointed 
government minister to allow him to retain his seat in the State 
Duma when he returns to his duties as administration head of the 
Shakhovskoy District, Moscow Region. 
  In compliance with the Constitution he had to abandon that 
position when he was elected to parliament. But he was 
reappointed to that position and simultaneously made a 
government minister on May 1. This enabled him to retain his 
seat in parliament. 
  Travkin made it clear that he had not been given any 
instructions on what he is to be doing in the government. He 
added he had not had any talks with Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin or any other minister on his new appointment. 
  Travkin thought that the government had to include somebody 
representing local interests. He attributed all failures of the 
reform to the inability of the government to hear what local 
officials had to say about its grandiose plans. Travkin thought 
that with his new appointment the government had an opportunity 
and had to use it. 
  He dismissed press reports on a split in his parliamentary 
group in the aftermath of his new appointment. He also thought 
that his signing of the Civic Accord Pact had nothing to do with 
the appointment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

