<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Makes Statement Prior to Talks With Kohl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Makes Statement Prior to Talks With Kohl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105161994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1408 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1105161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 11 May--"A new, complicated era will begin in 
bilateral relations after the withdrawal of Russian troops from 
Germany this August." Russian President Boris Yeltsin made this 
statement today before starting talks with German Chancellor 
Helmut Kohl. 
  The Russian opposition has been saying that "Germany will 
turn away from Russia completely after the withdrawal of Russian 
troops and will not help with its reforms, as it had been doing 
very actively in recent years under the leadership of Helmut 
Kohl." Answering this opposition, Yeltsin said: "I trust Helmut 
Kohl--his high moral standards, his decency, and his great 
political experience. An era of national reconciliation between 
two countries and two peoples--of Russia and Germany--will 
begin." 
  The Russian leader stressed that Russia wanted to be a full 
member of all European organizations. He reminded that Germany 
would be chair of the leading bodies of the European Union 
beginning 1 July 1994. "And, of course, we hope for support 
from Germany for Russia's participation in all of the European 
and international organizations," Yeltsin said. He especially 
stressed the importance of Russia as a European state. "Russia 
is a European country, and one should not forget this fact," 
the president said. 
  "During the course of today's hopefully peaceful, normal, 
human, but, of course, political and principled talks, I am sure 
that we will achieve together with my friend Helmut Kohl a full 
understanding and will settle the problems that we are facing 
today. They are there, and it is futile to make a secret of 
them," the president noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

