<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moldova, Gagauz Republic Heading Toward Peace Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moldova, Gagauz Republic Heading Toward Peace Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205083794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1442 
GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau], 11 May -- The leadership of 
Moldavia [Moldova] and the unrecognized Gagauz Republic have 
taken steps toward a peace settlement within the Gagauz problem. 
A meeting of the sides' parliamentary commissions is to take 
place in Kishinev on 12 May. They will discuss the draft law on 
the legal status of the Gagauz settlements. Today, it was 
discussed at a closed sitting of the commission of the Gagauz 
Parliament, which was attended by its president, Stepan Topal. 
The draft law grants the Gagauz people broad self-government 
within a single Moldavia. 
  According to Komrat (Gagauz capital) sources, disagreements 
appeared between the sides yesterday. They relate to the 
articles of the draft law, which define the status of the Gagauz 
rayons, their administration, and the division of powers between 
the republic's central leadership and local bodies. 
  Komrat's spokesmen proposed that changes should be made to 
the draft law, which envisages setting up the "Gagauz-eri" 
national and territorial entity in southern Moldavia. They 
insist on adopting their own constitution and are against the 
proposed procedure for appointing judges and heads of power 
bodies, which provides for their appointment by collegiums of 
the relevant Moldavian ministries. Kishinev disagrees with this. 
  Despite this, it looks as if the sides have managed to draw 
up compromise decisions, which will be discussed at tomorrow's 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

