<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   National Bank Disagrees With Monetary Union Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    National Bank Disagrees With Monetary Union Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205121094 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1000 GMT 
12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Bank of Belarus is not in favor of 
introducing Russia's customs duties in relation to third 
countries on the territory of the republic, because Russian 
export and import rates do not take into account the 
specifications of the Belarus economy. A correspondent from a 
financial information agency has learned this from a source at 
the Belarus Parliament. 
  According to the available information, a few days ago a 
parliamentary commission for the economic reform received an 
official reply from the National Bank of Belarus on its queery 
about the bank's stance with regard to the treaty on the 
unification of the monetary systems of Belarus and the Russian 
Federation, signed by the prime ministers of the two countries 
on 12 April in Moscow. The official reply makes it clear that 
the National Bank is critical of the treaty and believes that 
the gain from lifting customs duties is minimal in comparison 
with the burden of maintaining Russian strategic forces deployed 
on the territory of Belarus, which will fall on the Belarus 
state budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-62131 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov093_g_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Adopts Decision To Amend Law on National Bank </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Adopts Decision To Amend Law on National Bank </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1305101494 Minsk Radio Minsk Network in Belarusian 1715 
GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1305101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Radio Minsk Network </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The working meeting of the Belarusian Supreme Soviet 
commission for planning, budget, and finances has addressed the 
issue of noncash accounts between enterprises. Representatives 
of the Belarusian National Bank, the Ministry of Finances, the 
High Economic Court, and the Cabinet of Ministers participated 
in its work. The experts emphasized that given the recent 
economic slump, the breakdown of monetary and credit policies, 
the process of trading in [products] and balancing mutual 
accounts between suppliers and consumers has considerably 
exacerbated. As a result of inadequate finances, working 
capital is slow to be replenished. Debts for gas, electricity, 
and thermal energy are growing. Though current legislation 
regulates mutual accounts between economic sectors rather 
efficiently, some legal acts, particularly Clause No. 16 of the 
Law on the National Bank of Belarus, must be supplemented. The 
commission adopted a decision to discuss this issue at the 
session of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet and the Supreme 
Soviet session; to repeal and declare a range of legislative 
acts -- formulating economic pressure on enterprises -- as no 
longer effective; to task the Belarusian National Bank with 
determining the amount and mechanism for applying economic 
sanctions when balancing the noncash accounts of those who 
violate the law. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

