<H3> <TI>   Sakhalin, Japanese Companies To Fund Investment Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sakhalin, Japanese Companies To Fund Investment Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1205155394 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 12 May 94 p I </F>
<F P=103> PM1205155394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ADS report under the "Events of the Week" rubric: </F>
"`Sakhalin-Japan' Entrepreneurs' Association Established" -- 
from the FINANSOVYYE IZVESTIYA section] 
  [Text] On the Russian side, the association's founders 
include the International Center for Business Cooperation, 
"Sakhalinmoreneftegaz," the Sakhalin Shipping Line, 
"Sakhalinugol," and more than 30 other enterprises from 
Sakhalin; on the Japanese side the founders include a number of 
major companies such as Mitsui and the Bank of Tokyo. In 
accordance with its charter, the association intends to 
"formulate a set of investment projects and seeks to secure 
their implementation not for the sake of profit, but with a view 
to achieving all-around, mutually advantageous economic 
cooperation." The projects will be subsidized from the 
association's assets, which have been formed by contributions 
from its members. Mikhail Ryabtsev, director of the 
International Center for Business Cooperation 
(Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk), has been elected president. 

</TEXT>

