<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Admiral, Officers Refused Landing Permission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Admiral, Officers Refused Landing Permission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205185394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1614 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205185394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Navy Baltic Fleet Commander Vladimir Yegorov 
failed to arrive in Estonia today in order to supervise Russian 
troop withdrawal. The plane carrying Yegorov and a group of 
officers was refused landing in the Amari airport which remains 
in the disposition of the Russian Armed Forces. 
  Estonian Foreign Ministry Press Secretary Mari-Ann Rikken 
told Interfax that the appropriate notification had been 
transmitted by the Russian Embassy in Tallinn only two days 
before. She underlined that the internationally accepted norms 
demanded at least fifteen days for consideration. No 
information on the officers accompanying Yegorov had been given. 
Rikken said this had made impossible to authorize them to come 
to Estonia. 
  However, Russian Military Attache in Estonia Anatoliy 
Chizhikov told Interfax that Russia and Estonia had an agreement 
giving five days for consideration of notifications on landing 
of military jets, although such issues were as a rule resolved 
within one or two days. Chizhikov pointed out that the Russian 
Embassy had received no clarification on new terms for 
consideration of such notifications and refused to comment on 
the decision by the Estonian Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

