Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pledges Full Navy Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pledges Full Navy Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205141294 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1300 GMT 12 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>
<F P=105>  Latvian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Guntis Ulmanis met with Russian Ambassador 
Aleksandr Rannikh today. The Russian ambassador came at the 
president's invitation to discuss relations between the two 
countries. The Latvian president's letter to Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin was submitted to the ambassador. 
  Speaking of progress in implementing the Latvian-Russian 
agreements, Rannikh was concerned about Latvia's insufficient 
practical work in the area of the Skrunda new radar station. 
The Russian ambassador also told the president that at the 
beginning of June the last Russian Navy warship will leave 
Liepaja port and thus the Russian Navy will have completely left 
Latvia. 
  During the talks the opinion was expressed that the Latvian 
and Russian executive powers must act more responsibly and 
energetically so that the scheduled visit by Russian Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to Latvia can take place by the end 
of May. 
  Both the president and the ambassador assessed Latvia's 
recent joining of the Western European Union as an associate 
partner as a big success by Latvian diplomacy. Rannikh said 
that this event is evidence of the unified support by Europe and 
the Western European Union, which is an institution of European 
security, for the package of Latvian-Russia agreements signed in 
Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

