<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis Sends Yeltsin Letter on Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ulmanis Sends Yeltsin Letter on Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1305082894 Tallinn BNS in English 1507 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1305082894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, May 12, BNS -- Latvian President Guntis 
Ulmanis sent his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin a letter 
outlining a string of proposals for the formation of bilateral 
relations. 
  Ulmanis handed the letter over to Russian Ambassador 
Alexander Rannikh who visited him Thursday [12 May] to discuss 
Latvian- Russian relations. 
  Rannikh voiced his concern over "insufficient Latvian 
activities in the new block of the Skrunda radar facility," the 
president's office told BNS. 
  The ambassador told Ulmanis that the last Russian warship 
would leave the Liepaja seaport early in July, thus, marking the 
complete withdrawal of Russian naval forces from Latvia. 
  The officials pointed out that Latvian and Russian executive 
institutions should act more responsibly and energetically to 
allow for Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin's visit to 
Latvia later this month. 
  Ulmanis and Rannikh also assessed the recent Latvian joining 
to the Western European Union [WEU] in the status of "associate 
partner" as a major achievement of the Latvian diplomacy. 
  Rannikh claims that the event confirms the unanimous WEU and 
European Union's backing to the signed package of 
Latvian-Russian troop withdrawal treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

