<H4>    Russia Hopes To Repay Debt With MiGs </H4>

<F P=102> LD1305101994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1004 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1305101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Bonn May 13 TASS -- Russia wants to repay its debt 
to Germany with MiG-29 fighter planes and is ready to ship them 
immediately if Bonn agrees, according to Russian Economics 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin. 
  "If Germany takes MiG-29 planes we are ready to ship them", 
he told TASS on Friday and quoted President Boris Yeltsin as 
saying that "if necessary hundreds of fighters will arrive at 
local (German) airports in two days". 
  Shokhin added that one major project has been practically 
agreed upon during the visit of the Russian president to 
Germany. Bonn is to grant Russia a 500-million mark easy-term 
credit for buying railway cars produced in former east Germany. 
  Shokhin explained that it was impossible for Russia to 
manage 
the deal without the easy-term credit. Early this year Russia 
informed Bonn that the problem of shipping railway cars to 
Russia was irresolvable without privileged terms. The German 
Government met the Russian request although it was fraught with 
a certain confrontation with the Organisation of Economic 
Cooperation and Development, Shokhin said. 
  This is a 10-year easy-term credit granted under government 
guarantees, Shokhin said and added that the terms are suitable 
for Russia and will not negatively affect its budget deficit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

