<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Yeltsin's Visit to Germany </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Yeltsin's Visit to Germany </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Statement on Trade Issues Released </H4>

<F P=102> LD1205162594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1525 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 12 TASS--In reply to Russian press 
reports on difficulties in bilateral trade, which had allegedly 
arisen through the fault of the German side, the FRG Embassy in 
Moscow has asked BUSINESS-TASS to publish its press statement, 
explaining the German view on this question. 
  The document notes, specifically, that, taking into account 
the new German federal lands' difficult adaptation to the market 
economy, the members of the Organisation for Economic 
Cooperation and Development (OECD) had agreed to grant Germany 
easy terms for crediting export trade during the transition 
period. Such credit guarantees were issued to the sum of 8.2 
billion German marks in the period from 1992 to 1993. This 
meant that German companies could export their goods to Russia 
while payment for such deliveries was guaranteed on easy terms, 
within the limits of the indicated sum, by the "Hermes 
Kredit-Versicherungds-Ag" company. 
  The point is that the German Government does not handle 
administrative and technical matters linked with the insurance 
of export credits. This job is entrusted to the foregoing 
private firm, but decisions to grant credits are made by four 
ministries: the Ministry of Finance, the Ministry of Economics, 
the Foreign Ministry, and the Ministry for Economic Cooperation. 
  The embassy's statement points out that the conclusion of 
many contracts with Russian firms on the basis of the above-said 
preferential guarantees was delayed for different reasons and 
now they can no longer be applied, because the preferences were 
annulled beginning from January 1, 1994. The authors of the 
statement claim that the Russian side was notified about all 
this in advance. 
  Nevertheless, export guarantees for goods delivered to 
Russia 
are still being granted, but now on general terms, corresponding 
to the international practice and on agreement with credit 
insurers within the OECD. For instance, advance and 
intermediate payments, amounting to no less than 15 per cent of 
the total cost of the deal, have to be made if it is financed 
for a term of over 360 days. No preferential period is 
envisaged. 
  Therefore, the statement of the FRG Embassy notes, there is 
no deterioration of crediting terms, simply the period for 
granting temporary preferences has expired. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-62155 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov093_a_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reportage on Yeltsin's Visit to Germany </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continued Reportage on Yeltsin's Visit to Germany </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Visit Gives Yeltsin `Moral Support' </H4>

<F P=102> PM1205125394 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 12 May 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PM1205125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Ravil Zaripov and Igor Yavlyanskiy report under the </F>
"Visits" rubric: "Final Parade Imminent"] 
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- You will not believe it but Yeltsin 
brought good weather with him to the banks of the Rhine. As the 
government airplane approached the Bonn-Cologne airport, the fog 
which until then had formed a thick shroud over the 
Siebengebirge drifted off somewhere. 
  Boris Nikolayevich alighted from the airplane when the sky 
had already cleared and a gentle sun was shining. We, of 
course, are no experts in physiognomy but will make so bold as 
to assert that the Russian president stepped onto German soil in 
a good frame of mind. He even found an opportunity to give a 
short interview by the steps of the airplane, though this was 
not stipulated by the protocol. 
  "I want to sum up with my friend Helmut the results of the 
two-year period since my last official visit to Bonn. We will 
discuss -- what is more for the final time -- the arrangements 
for withdrawing our troops from the FRG. Right down to the last 
soldier. We intend to firmly insist that the celebratory 
ceremony be held in Berlin." 
  Matvey Burlakov, commander of the Western Group of Forces, 
is 
one of those who intend to insist to the end that Berlin is the 
location. In addition to the arguments which have already been 
presented, he added his own simplehearted soldier's argument: 
"But 31 August (the completion date for our troops' withdrawal) 
is a working day in Germany. Who will we have to take our leave 
of? It is necessary to organize the send-off on a nonworking 
day so that people come. It would be desirable to hold a 
meeting in the Reichstag." 
  During the current visit, the heads of state will not sign 
agreements and protocols. The only exception that has been made 
is for the so-called "red" telephone -- the direct link between 
the Kremlin and the Federal Chancellery. Foreign Ministers 
Andrey Kozyrev and Klaus Kinkel will confirm its right to exist 
by adding their signatures. 
  Informed sources in the FRG Ministry of Foreign Affairs tell 
us that the German leadership views this visit as an opportunity 
to give Boris Nikolayevich "moral support." Bonn officials will 
do all they can to make the high-ranking Russian guest feel that 
he is head of a great power. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

