<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Denies Forces Sought Joint Sendoff With Allies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Denies Forces Sought Joint Sendoff With Allies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205201894 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Begin recording] [Correspondent] Yeltsin and Kohl 
reached a decision on the sendoff ceremony for Russian troops in 
Berlin. [Video shows Defense Minister Pavel Grachev being 
interviewed] 
  Pavel Sergeyevich, now that the president and the chancellor 
have reached agreement on holding the ceremony in Berlin, can we 
say that all the problems connected with withdrawing our troops 
from Germany have been settled? 
  [Grachev] You cannot say that all the problems connected 
with 
withdrawing our troops have been settled. The fact is there are 
fundamental political decisions by the chancellor and our 
president. The ceremonial sendoff of the troops will take place 
from Berlin. Now the onus is on us. 
  [Correspondent] There were plenty of discussions in the 
German press about the Russian military insisting, I emphasize 
insisting, that the ceremonial sendoff be with the Allies. In 
order for there not to be any misunderstanding here, perhaps you 
could comment on this. 
  [Grachev] This is really a misunderstanding. I do not want 
to say that this is some sort of provocation, provocative 
questions; no, this is purely and simply a misunderstanding. 
We were not insisting, we were not even suggesting that the 
withdrawal should be organized together and simultaneously with 
the Allies. The timescale was laid down a long time ago. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

