<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Urges Settlement of Tajik Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Urges Settlement of Tajik Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205165394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1250 
GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Aleksandr Krulovich </F>
and Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 12 May -- The Russian Foreign Ministry today 
called on the Tajik opposition, military, and political 
groupings in Afghanistan and the involved states to do 
everything possible in order not to allow the situation on the 
Tajik-Afghan border to aggravate. Mikhail Demurin, deputy 
director of the Press and Information Directorate of the Russian 
foreign policy department, said this addressing a briefing today. 
  He said that "one of the priorities in Russian foreign 
policy" at present was to assist in settling the Tajik conflict 
and to restore peace and calm in the country. In the diplomat's 
words, great importance is being attached to the continuation of 
the inter-Tajik talks that started with the Moscow round. The 
world's response to its results shows that "great hopes are 
being linked with the progress of the dialogue." 
  Demurin stated with regret that this approach was not being 
shared by everyone--the recalcitrant part of the Tajik armed 
opposition, supported by Afghan mojahedins, is concentrating its 
forces on the border. This is increasing the danger of 
"large-scale hostilities," the Russian Foreign Ministry 
spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

