<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Welcomes Nagorno-Karabakh Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205191494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1614 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Foreign Ministry has welcomed the 
agreement on ceasefire in Nagorno-Karabakh and insisted that it 
be strictly implemented by all parties. This was announced by 
an official representative of the Russian Foreign Ministry, 
Mikhail Demurin, at a briefing in Moscow today. 
  He said it was necessary to achieve a breakthrough in 
development of the situation, to turn to peace and to confirm 
the armistice with a legally binding agreement which would put 
an end to the armed conflict once and for all. 
  Demurin announced that the agreement on ceasefire had been 
reached on May 12 late at night by the Armenian and Azerbaijani 
defense ministers and the commander of the Nagorno-Karabakh army 
with a significant contribution made by Russia and the chairman 
of the CSCE Minsk Group on Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  "Contrary to the ceasefires unilaterally declared by 
Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan this agreement provides for 
mutual obligations of the parties and a compromise reached with 
the participation of the mediators," Demurin stressed. 

</TEXT>

