<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Hopes Turkey Changes Stance on Black Sea Straits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Hopes Turkey Changes Stance on Black Sea Straits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205211594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1934 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian government considers it unacceptable to 
change unilaterally the present international regulation of 
navigation in the Black Sea gulfs and hopes that Turkey will 
review its position on this issue. This was said in a note sent 
by the Russian Foreign Ministry to the Turkish Embassy on April 
29 in connection with the adoption of a navigation regulation in 
the Black Sea gulfs by the Turkish government, an official 
representative of the Russian Foreign Ministry Mikhail Demurin 
said at a news briefing in Moscow on Thursday. 
  In his words, "a number of articles of the regulation 
adopted 
by Turkey envisages the procedure of passage through the gulfs 
and considerable restrictions up to the complete ban on such 
passage for certain categories of vessels depending on their 
length, draft, cargo, etc." Demurin said that these articles of 
the regulation go beyond issues of navigational safety and 
contradict international convention. 
  In Demurin's opinion "the steps taken by the Turkish side 
regarding the gulfs can create unnecessary complications in this 
region. They should be perceived as an attempt to replace 
international regulation on this issue by domestic legislation." 

</TEXT>

