<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Rejects Monitoring of Submarine Dismantling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Rejects Monitoring of Submarine Dismantling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1305111094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1058 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1305111094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, May 13 (YONHAP) -- North Korea keeps 
shunning a Russian expert's witness of the disintegration of a 
submarine they had purchased from Russia supposedly for use as 
scrap, it was learned here on Friday. 
  Officials at the Russian Defense Ministry said his Ministry 
had several times asked North Korea to accept a Russian expert's 
witness of the disintegration of a discarded Russian submarine 
delivered to them last December. But, North Korea has not 
affirmatively responded, they said. 
  Western sources here said North Korea seems to have already 
begun disintegrating the submarine. 
  "As they reject a Russian expert's presence, there is the 
strong possibility that they may recycle the submarine for 
military purpose," the sources said. 
  They said that despite North Korea's rejection of such 
witness, the Russian Pacific Fleet has decided to deliver more 
discarded submarines to North Korea. 
  Last November, North Korea signed a contract with Russia for 
the purchase of 12 discarded Russian submarines for use as 
"scrap." 
  The contract provides for a Russian expert's witness of the 
disintegration of the submarines delivered so as to dispel the 
possibility of them being recycled militarily in North Korea. 
  One of the submarines was delivered to North Korea last 
December and a North Korean tugboat is presently in Vladivostok 
preparing to tow another. 

</TEXT>

