<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Comment on Nagorno-Karabakh Settlement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Comment on Nagorno-Karabakh Settlement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205173994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1614 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] INTERFAX has learned that a confidential meeting 
between Azerbaijani leader Heydar Aliyev and other officials and 
the plenipotentiary representative of the Russian president for 
the Nagorno-Karabakh settlement, Vladimir Kazimirov, could be 
held Thursday [12 May]. 
  Besides other issues, the meeting will focus on the date and 
agenda of the Azerbaijani-Armenian summit planned to be held in 
Moscow. 
  IF Note: In an interview with INTERFAX, Armenian 
Presidential Assistant Levon Zurabyan confirmed the possibility 
of such a meeting under Russia's auspices. He said pleparatory 
diplomatic activities were carried out through the mediation by 
the Russian side. As has been reported, the 
Azerbaijani-Armenian summit planned to be held during the CIS 
April summit was disrupted. Armenia has been maintaining that 
the reason for the disruption was Azerbaijan's reluctance to 
accept the Russian plan for the settlement in Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  In an interview with INTERFAX, Kazimirov pointed out that an 
Azerbaijani-Armenian summit could be useful on a rather advanced 
stage of consideration of the draft settlement agreement," based 
on the Russian design. 
  Kazimirov pointed out the main provisions of the Russian 
settlement plan. The first stage is "short, but crucial and 
complicated" -- the establishment of a cease-fire. The second 
stage involves a shift to the elimination of consequences of the 
armed conflict, including a withdrawal of troops from the 
occupied territories, exchange of prisoners of war, hostages, 
bodies of the killed, information of those missing in action or 
killed, re-introduction of the transport and power lines and the 
repatriation of refugees to their permanent locations. On the 
third stage, political talks on the future legal status of 
Nagorno-Karabakh will be launched. 
  "Whenever the sides are close enough to signing such a draft 
agreement, such a meeting in Moscow will be possible," Kazimirov 
was quoted as saying. 
  Zurabyan said the Moscow summit was envisioned by a protocol 
signed at the meeting of Armenian, Azerbaijani and 
Nagorno-Karabakh parliamentarians in Bishkek on 5 May through 
the mediation of the CIS Interparliamentary Assembly. 
  IF Note: Azerbaijani Parliamentary Speaker Rasul Guliyev who 
signed the document with a number of stipulations came under 
harsh criticisms by the parliamentary opposition, the National 
Independence Party lead by Etibar Mamedov. According to the 
party, Guliyev committed high treason by signing the Bishkek 
protocol "together with the leader of the Supreme Soviet of a 
non-existent so-called Nagorno-Karabakh Republic, Karen 
Baburyan." The party said Guliyev "created all necessary 
conditions for the recognition of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic 
as a subject of the international law and open the possibility 
for concluding an agreement which would legalize the deployment 
of Russian troops in Azerbaijan." 
  In the meantime, Nagorno-Karabakh Foreign Minister Arkady 
Gukasyan did not preclude that the reports on Azerbaijan's 
signing the Bishkek protocol on the settlement in 
Nagorno-Karabakh on 8 May were another tactical step by Baku. 
In Gukasyan's opinion, only the deployment of peacekeeping 
forces was capable of putting an end to the bloodshed. 
  Azerbaijani Defense Minister Mamadrafi Mammadov, his 
Armenian 
counterpart, Serzh Sargsyan, and the Nagorno-Karabakh troops 
commander, Samvel Babayan, signed an agreement Wednesday 
midnight to cease-fire as of 0000 on 12 May, Interfax learned 
from well-informed sources from in Stepanakert. 
  Meanwhile, the Nagorno-Karabakh Army press service reported 
fierce fighting along the frontline, despite the cease-fire 
agreement signed. The press service said that after a heavy 
shelling Azerbaijani troops attempted to break the 
Nagorno-Karabakh defense near the village of Yusifdzhanly of the 
Agdam district at about 0700 Thursday. 
  The Azerbaijani Defense Ministry reported Armenian units had 
tried to develop their offensive on Geranboi and Agdam yesterday 
night. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

