<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stepanakert Not Sure Baku Will Observe Bishkek Protocol </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stepanakert Not Sure Baku Will Observe Bishkek Protocol </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105204694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Foreign Minister of the self-proclaimed 
Nagorno-Karabakh Republic Arkady Gukasian does not rule out the 
possibility that reports about Azerbaijan signing the Bishkek 
protocol of a settlement in Karabakh on 8 May is another 
tactical move on the part of Baku. He said Stepanakert has not 
yet received the protocol signed by the speaker of the Azeri 
parliament Rasul Guliyev. 
  In a Wednesday [11 May] interview with INTERFAX Gukasian 
said 
that in reality the Azeri side is psychologically not ready for 
the peaceful settlement of the conflict. He named as evidence 
the situation on the front-line where Azeri troops continue 
attacking Karabakh positions. 
  Gukasian stressed that a political settlement is impossible 
without guarantees of a complete cease-fire. He also declared 
that Nagorno-Karabakh should be recognized as a conflicting 
side. In his opinion only the deployment of a peace-keeping 
force in the conflict zone can stop the bloodshed. 

</TEXT>

