Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhaz Official Favors Presence of CIS or UN Forces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abkhaz Official Favors Presence of CIS or UN Forces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1305103194 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 0800 
GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1305103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Igor Akhba, envoy of the so-called Abkhazia to the 
Russian Federation, has declared that it is all the same for 
Abkhazia who plays the role of peacekeeping forces -- UN forces 
or CIS special units. According to Akhba, the key issue is the 
deployment of forces solely in the buffer zone. 
  The clause in the agreement on the deployment of troops in 
the conflict zone, unexpectedly for the Georgian side, was 
presented by representatives of Russia, the UN, and the European 
Union. 
  In the opinion of Georgian delegation members, the Abkhaz 
version of the settlement of the conflict suits the UN, the 
European Union, and Russia, because should CIS troops rather 
than UN forces enter the conflict zone, the issue of financing 
the troops will automatically be resolved as the CIS states and 
Georgia will have to undertake this task. 
  According to some analysts, Georgia's signing of this 
document could exacerbate the domestic political situation in 
Georgia. 
  Talks are continuing in Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

