<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rutskoy Says Opposition Will Unite To Take Power </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rutskoy Says Opposition Will Unite To Take Power </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205202494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1841 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Belskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 12 TASS -- Russian Former Vice-President 
Aleksandr Rutskoy called upon all opposition forces to unite in 
a bid to take power in the country. 
  Speaking at a meeting held today in Moscow "Izmailovo" 
sports 
complex, the leader of last year hard-line revolt in Moscow, 
said addressing leaders of different opposition parties and 
patriotic movements: "It is high time to stop arguing who is 
right and who is wrong. We have one objective, we have one 
motherland... Everyone must realise that unity is power now". 
  Rutskoy reiterated his declaration of May 9 that the main 
task of the opposition is to spare no efforts ensuring that "the 
next Victory Day (May 9, 1995) would be marked without the 
regime which rules now". 
  The meeting was attended by the most influential opposition 
leaders, such as Viktor Anpilov (Labour Russia), Sergey Baburin 
(Russian All-National Union), Ilya Konstantinov (Front of 
National Salvation), Generals Makashov and Achalov. 
  Meanwhile, Russian television aired an interview with 
Rutskoy 
in which ex-vice-president practically denied the proclaimed 
intention to come to power before next spring. 
  In the televised interview Rutskoy declared a contradicting 
plan according to which a would-be social-patriotic party, 
apparently headed by Rutskoy himself, shall win up to 90 per 
cent of seats in the parliamentary elections in 1995, and then 
enter presidential election race scheduled for 1996. 

</TEXT>

