<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dubinin Approves, Gaydar Opposes 1994 Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dubinin Approves, Gaydar Opposes 1994 Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205115394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0918 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205115394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By BUSINESS-TASS correspondent Robert Serebrennikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 12 TASS -- "The approved state budget is 
more realistic than ever before: it offers an opportunity to 
follow an economic course chosen by the government as well," 
said Acting Finance Minister Sergey Dubinin, commenting on the 
Duma's decision to approve a draft law on federal budget of the 
Russian Federation for 1994 in the first reading. 
  "According to specified data, the budget was endorsed at 
194.4 trillion rubles for expenditures and 124.4 trillion rubles 
for revenues. The top limit of the budget deficit was estimated 
at 70 trillion rubles, or 36 per cent of budgetary expenditures. 
A decision was adopted to look into the problem of more 
rational use of funds envisaged as financial aid to subjects of 
the federation," Dubinin said in an interview with ITAR-TASS. 
  However, leader of the Russia's Choice faction Yegor Gaydar 
believes that the approval of the federal budget by the State 
Duma means that a negative tendency which appeared in spring, 
1994 will continue to develop. The essence of this tendency is 
a step-by-step increase in subsidies, growing expenditures 
envisaged by "investments and subsidies" articles with 
simultaneous cuts in social allocations, in particular, for 
culture, science and education. 
  In an interview with BUSINESS-TASS prominent Russian 
economist Grigoriy Yavlinskiy said that the federal budget in 
its present form will not change anything and the situation in 
the country will be the same as it was before. "Lawmakers do 
not realise that the budget is the money of all citizens which 
should be correctly used to prevent the situation from getting 
worse," Yavlisnkiy said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-62228 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov093_b_94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dubinin: Approval `Recognition of Policy' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dubinin: Approval `Recognition of Policy' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205192794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1614 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian acting Finance Minister Sergey Dubinin told 
Interfax Thursday that he considered the State Duma's passing of 
the draft federal budget for 1994 at first hearing as a 
recognition of the economic policy pursued by the government. 
  Dubinin said the collection rate of taxes fluctuated around 
60 percent at the moment, which is obviously insufficient. The 
Finance Ministry put forward a number of proposals to increase 
the tax influx to the state budget. In part, the proposals 
involve taxation bodies' registering all accounts of 
enterprises, including hard currency ones, and collecting taxes 
directly from the accounts. 
  At the same time, Dubinin pointed out that the tax basis 
shrank due to an economic decline. He said taxes collected in 
the first quarter of 1994 were equal to seven percent of the 
gross domestic product against 10 percent last year. In March, 
the situation was stabilized at last year's level, he added. 
  Dubinin supported further improvement of the existing 
taxation system which needed adjustment rather than reformation. 
"The existing set of taxes may be reduced, but not changed for 
another one," he pointed out. Dubinin put a special emphasis 
on the fact that the federation items had been granted the right 
to impose their own taxes, a right which it would be "very 
unreasonable to take away from them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-62229 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov093_b_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-093 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dubinin Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dubinin Holds News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205192994 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1205192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Confidence in government policy has been obtained 
from the State Duma. This was stated at a news conference today 
by the acting finance minister. Sergey Dubinin noted that 
deputies' criticisms will be taken into account in the 
finalization of the budget. Therefore, he did not rule out the 
possibility of a future reduction in the state's administrative 
apparatus in favor of increased expenditures on science. 
Dubinin said that the government will endeavor to submit the 
1995 budget to parliament as early as September. Moreover, it 
will be drawn up while taking into account a reform of taxation 
policy. The supervision of all the accounts of enterprises, 
including their hard currency, will be more strict. 
  Dwelling on privatization, Dubinin said that it has not 
brought the budget any real revenue, since the ideology behind 
it was based from the outset on a free handout of state 
property. Forecasting the level of inflation, Dubinin noted 
that it would be under 10 percent. By the end of the year, a 
level of between 5 and 7 percent is quite realistic. In his 
view, the exchange rate for the dollar will not rise above 3,000 
rubles. 

</TEXT>

