<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unions Reserve Right To Strike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Unions Reserve Right To Strike </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205125094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1015 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mikhail Shmakov, leader of the Federation of 
Independent Trade Unions of Russia, outlined in a letter to the 
Kremlin chief of staff and the chairman of the Yeltsin-sponsored 
Public Chamber, the Federation's own view on the Civic Accord 
which it signed in Moscow 28 April. 
  To begin with, the Federation says there can be no question 
of a moratorium on strikes. The unions, it says, reserve the 
right to collective action if the government fails to comply 
with accords on pay and work conditions, employment, and social 
security guarantees. 
  The Federation insists that the government must clear its 
debt of back wages in the first half of 1994 rather than later 
in the year and help keep intact the existing system of free 
secondary and vocational education, something that the Accord 
does not guarantee. 
  The Federation also demands that its special view is made 
known to the conciliatory commission and used as a basis for 
further talks with government officials on controversial points 
of the Accord. 

</TEXT>

