<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Official Says Budget Inadequate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Official Says Budget Inadequate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205143494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1315 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 12 TASS -- "The Russian military budget 
of 37 trillion roubles, approved by the State Duma for the 
current year, does not guarantee the survival of the Russian 
Army, ITAR-TASS was told by head of the Defence Ministry's chief 
budget and finance board Colonel-General Vasiliy Vorobyov. 
  In the opinion of the Defence Ministry, all the articles of 
the military budget are underfinanced. Particularly alarming is 
the problem of cash allowances to servicemen. The Russian 
Finance Ministry monthly issues funds for this purpose which are 
not enough to pay allowances to one-third of the officers and 
noncoms. Under the new budget 50 per cent of the personnel will 
get their cash allowances with intervals, sometimes lasting from 
two to three months. "The situation is also alarming as regards 
allocations for armaments, military hardware, property, capital 
repairs and maintenance, scientific and technological needs," 
Vorobyov stated. 
  Shortage of money for the minimum requirements of the Army, 
the latter's insolvency has brought about a situation when some 
regional authorities have begun to cut off electric power supply 
to military installations, ensuring Russia's security. For 
instance, power workers of Archangel region had cut off power 
supply to a considerable part of the local strategic missile 
forces testing ground. Notifications are being received 
regularly by anti-aircraft defence units, including their 
central command station. "It is clear to everybody, even to a 
person poorly versed in national security problems, that such a 
situation is frought with very dangerous consequences," the 
general stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

