<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Operation To Catch Illegal Fishers Modified </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Operation To Catch Illegal Fishers Modified </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1205140694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1015 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1205140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Pacific Fleet has changed the composition of 
ships taking part in the Putina-94 operation aimed at combating 
illegal sea fishing in the Far East. 
  Throughout several weeks of the first stage, from April 20 
to 
May 10, two trawlers controlled the catch and the use of fish 
resources of Russia in the Aniv Bay. They are to be replaced by 
two sea trawlers which will patrol in the Sea of Japan, Interfax 
was told by a spokesman for the Pacific Fleet. 
  During the first stage of the operation, crews of over 20 
Russian and four foreign vessels were brought to justice, 
Interfax was told by the commander of the Pacific Border Guard 
District, Major General Vitaliy Sedykh. 
  He said that about 700 vessels, including 200 foreign ones 
were spotted in Russia's economic zone. Of this number, over 
100 Russian and over 20 foreign vessels have been checked. 
  Besides the Pacific Fleet, taking part in the operation were 
vessels of the Pacific Border Guard District, vessels of fish 
protection organizations Primorryba and Sakhrybvoda, staff 
members of the federal counterintelligence service and of the 
Far Eastern customs department. 

</TEXT>

