<H3> <TI>   New Committee Seeks `Substantial' Military Powers in Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Committee Seeks `Substantial' Military Powers in Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1305102294 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 0500 GMT 13 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1305102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Creation of the standing legislative Commission for 
Military Issues, Security, and Protection of Servicemen's Rights 
became a sensation at yesterday's session of the Crimean Supreme 
Soviet. A report delivered by Mykhaylo Kukushkin, head of the 
commission and commander of the Black Sea Fleet Air Force 
Administration, shows that the commission will be seeking 
substantial powers. In his words, the deputies should watch the 
movements of all troops on Crimean territory. All military 
exercises in the Crimea and visits by military ships to local 
ports can only be conducted when permitted by the Crimean 
president. The new commission intends to assume control over 
the activities of the Crimean Security Service. 

